        <h2>Part 4: S3 Bucket for Data Upload (30 minutes)</h2>

        <h3>Step 10: Create S3 Bucket</h3>
        <pre><code class="language-bash"># Create bucket
export BUCKET_NAME="data-pipeline-uploads-$(aws sts get-caller-identity --query Account --output text)"

aws s3 mb s3://$BUCKET_NAME

echo "S3 Bucket: $BUCKET_NAME"</code></pre>

        <h3>Step 11: Create Sample CSV Data</h3>
        <p><strong>Create <code>sample-sales.csv</code>:</strong></p>

        <pre><code>date,product,quantity,revenue,region
2024-01-01,Widget A,100,1500.00,North
2024-01-01,Widget B,75,1125.50,South
2024-01-01,Gadget X,50,2500.00,East
2024-01-02,Widget A,120,1800.00,North
2024-01-02,Gadget Y,30,900.00,West
2024-01-03,Widget B,200,3000.00,South</code></pre>

        <p><strong>What's happening here?</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Created an S3 bucket to receive data uploads</li>
          <li>Prepared sample CSV data to test the pipeline</li>
          <li>This bucket will be the trigger for our data processing</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>The event-driven pattern</strong>:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>User/System uploads CSV to S3</li>
          <li>S3 sends event notification</li>
          <li>Lambda automatically processes the file</li>
          <li>Data lands in RDS, cache gets invalidated</li>
          <li>No servers to manage, scales automatically!</li>
        </ol>

        <p><strong>Pro tip</strong>: S3 event notifications are the foundation of serverless data pipelines. They're instant, reliable, and free!</p>
